WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.120
Hi everyone, my name is Liz Roten, and today I'm going to talk to you about how you can

00:00:11.120 --> 00:00:18.879
take the project that you really hate and turn it into something oddly satisfying.

00:00:18.879 --> 00:00:21.719
So this adventure starts with a truck.

00:00:21.719 --> 00:00:24.200
Or rather, a truck corridor study.

00:00:24.200 --> 00:00:28.040
Hey, there we go.

00:00:28.040 --> 00:00:34.680
My manager pitched this project to me as a straightforward, quick data science win.

00:00:34.680 --> 00:00:37.959
The only thing we needed to do was update the data.

00:00:37.959 --> 00:00:42.720
All of the methods and extra analysis were settled.

00:00:42.720 --> 00:00:45.200
It was going to be very easy.

00:00:45.200 --> 00:00:47.919
And it wasn't.

00:00:47.919 --> 00:00:54.599
And my first inkling of this was when I started to look into the project materials.

00:00:54.599 --> 00:00:55.599
They were bad.

00:00:55.599 --> 00:00:57.919
They were pretty bad.

00:00:57.919 --> 00:01:00.599
And how bad are we talking here?

00:01:00.599 --> 00:01:05.599
So on the left, you can see a bunch of files, and the font is way too small, because there

00:01:05.599 --> 00:01:08.320
are simply too many.

00:01:08.320 --> 00:01:10.980
And there are a couple of things I want to point out.

00:01:10.980 --> 00:01:15.199
So there are multiple final reports.

00:01:15.199 --> 00:01:20.400
And the problem when you have something and you name it and you have multiple things and

00:01:20.400 --> 00:01:27.160
you name all of them final, the word final stops meaning anything.

00:01:27.160 --> 00:01:33.320
There's no telling what actually truly is the final document.

00:01:33.320 --> 00:01:36.839
There are also multiple documents that were marked as revised.

00:01:36.839 --> 00:01:37.839
Great.

00:01:37.839 --> 00:01:39.680
Marked as revised.

00:01:39.680 --> 00:01:44.080
And marked revised maybe August 11th or August 14th.

00:01:44.080 --> 00:01:49.400
However, when this project first took place, it took place over more than one year.

00:01:49.400 --> 00:01:54.099
So was it August 2017 or 2018?

00:01:54.099 --> 00:01:56.440
I don't have any information from that.

00:01:56.440 --> 00:02:05.959
And I don't know who modified it or revised it, when they revised it or why it was revised.

00:02:05.959 --> 00:02:12.119
And there is a single Excel workbook with all the analysis, including a worksheet with

00:02:12.119 --> 00:02:21.759
over 15,000 rows and a whole bunch of nasty formulas that will make your skin crawl.

00:02:21.759 --> 00:02:25.820
And so now that I've introduced you to this mess, I'd like to pivot to something a little

00:02:25.820 --> 00:02:26.820
better.

00:02:26.820 --> 00:02:33.539
And it's this Internet phenomenon of things that are oddly satisfying.

00:02:33.539 --> 00:02:40.520
So oddly satisfying things is a content of a genre of content.

00:02:40.520 --> 00:02:45.059
And it's generally something like someone taking something super dirty and making it

00:02:45.059 --> 00:02:47.300
pristinely clean.

00:02:47.300 --> 00:02:52.139
Or painting something very precisely.

00:02:52.139 --> 00:02:59.179
I, in my opinion, find this tiny crab holding up a tiny fish very satisfying.

00:02:59.179 --> 00:03:03.699
With the composition, you have the yellow and the blue and the foreground and the background.

00:03:03.699 --> 00:03:05.699
I think it's satisfying.

00:03:05.699 --> 00:03:13.360
But in case that doesn't really do it for you, I have a couple more.

00:03:13.360 --> 00:03:16.699
So this first video is of a person with a smoothie.

00:03:16.699 --> 00:03:19.539
They add this purple powder into the smoothie.

00:03:19.539 --> 00:03:25.699
And you see the color come in to the smoothie as it's, like, smoothing around.

00:03:25.699 --> 00:03:29.100
And it's very mesmerizing.

00:03:29.100 --> 00:03:30.100
And lovely.

00:03:30.100 --> 00:03:32.960
And I have one more.

00:03:32.960 --> 00:03:38.979
And that's of a person using a turntable to ice a tart.

00:03:38.979 --> 00:03:44.500
So you see the little tart, you see the turntable turning and a person using a piping bag to

00:03:44.500 --> 00:03:48.339
pipe this perfect spiral.

00:03:48.339 --> 00:03:57.139
And then once the spiral is complete, they grab a blowtorch, get a little color on there.

00:03:57.139 --> 00:04:04.339
And finally, they pan over to all of the other absolutely beautiful, identical tarts.

00:04:04.339 --> 00:04:10.880
And there's something about these videos that just soothes my soul.

00:04:10.880 --> 00:04:20.480
And so I had this moment of what if I take the truck study and make it this satisfying?

00:04:20.480 --> 00:04:27.880
I essentially decided to take my truck that made me very sad and turn it into the best

00:04:27.880 --> 00:04:31.600
truck that has ever existed.

00:04:31.600 --> 00:04:37.040
And I learned a few things along the way that I'd like to share with you.

00:04:37.040 --> 00:04:39.559
And they come in three.

00:04:39.559 --> 00:04:42.399
First, assess the damage.

00:04:42.399 --> 00:04:46.760
Second, do and document.

00:04:46.760 --> 00:04:52.059
And finally, leave a gift.

00:04:52.059 --> 00:04:57.000
So let's assess the damage.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:00.920
You're essentially going to complete a project intake.

00:05:00.920 --> 00:05:04.160
Start by reading through everything.

00:05:04.160 --> 00:05:07.160
And I mean actually everything.

00:05:07.160 --> 00:05:11.079
The more you read through now, the fewer surprises you're going to have later on and

00:05:11.079 --> 00:05:15.959
the better feel you're going to have for the project itself.

00:05:15.959 --> 00:05:19.839
As you're doing this, you're going to make a hate list.

00:05:19.839 --> 00:05:25.359
Which is a list of all of the things about this project that you hate.

00:05:25.359 --> 00:05:27.579
Maybe the documentation is vague.

00:05:27.579 --> 00:05:33.320
Maybe the documentation and the calculation aren't doing the same thing that they should

00:05:33.320 --> 00:05:35.679
be doing.

00:05:35.679 --> 00:05:41.279
Whatever it is, write it down and put it aside for later.

00:05:41.279 --> 00:05:47.200
You're also going to replicate your findings or the results from the previous study, if

00:05:47.200 --> 00:05:48.239
applicable.

00:05:48.239 --> 00:05:52.519
And this is going to test your knowledge of this project.

00:05:52.519 --> 00:05:56.920
And it's going to give you an opportunity to work through it hands on.

00:05:56.920 --> 00:06:02.399
And even if the numbers don't align exactly, you need to be able to explain why they don't

00:06:02.399 --> 00:06:04.160
align exactly.

00:06:04.160 --> 00:06:07.480
Was it a rounding issue or a data source issue?

00:06:07.480 --> 00:06:11.359
Whatever it is, you just need to explain it.

00:06:11.359 --> 00:06:19.700
And the most important part of your intake is finding your thing.

00:06:19.700 --> 00:06:27.880
And your thing is this one aspect or multiple of your professional life that makes you excited.

00:06:27.880 --> 00:06:33.200
Something that you know you can work on and you can be proud of.

00:06:33.320 --> 00:06:39.839
You're going to find a way to apply your thing to this project.

00:06:39.839 --> 00:06:42.160
Maybe you're really into plots.

00:06:42.160 --> 00:06:54.279
You're going to go out and find all of the ggplot2 extensions and make beautiful plots.

00:06:54.279 --> 00:06:56.559
Or perhaps you're into maps.

00:06:56.559 --> 00:07:01.959
You're going to make some maps with some excellent legend work and it will all look

00:07:01.959 --> 00:07:05.079
wonderful.

00:07:05.079 --> 00:07:08.359
Or maybe you're into speed and efficiency.

00:07:08.359 --> 00:07:14.399
Break out all of your vector-based programming skills and make this thing lightning fast.

00:07:14.399 --> 00:07:21.519
Whatever it is, it's important that it's yours and it's important that you get excited about

00:07:21.519 --> 00:07:25.320
doing it.

00:07:25.320 --> 00:07:33.399
Your thing is what's going to power this project and it will also keep you sane.

00:07:33.399 --> 00:07:37.359
And my thing is documentation.

00:07:37.359 --> 00:07:44.480
If you're ever unsure of what your thing could be with a project, try documentation.

00:07:44.480 --> 00:07:46.480
And that leads us to the second part.

00:07:46.480 --> 00:07:50.519
To do and document.

00:07:50.519 --> 00:07:52.959
So you're going to do the thing.

00:07:52.959 --> 00:07:54.320
Complete the work.

00:07:54.320 --> 00:07:57.760
And you're going to document along the way.

00:07:57.760 --> 00:08:03.320
There is one sentence that I think encapsulates why documentation is so important better than

00:08:03.320 --> 00:08:05.220
anything else.

00:08:05.220 --> 00:08:07.279
And that is this quote.

00:08:07.279 --> 00:08:13.320
That documentation is a love letter to your future self.

00:08:13.320 --> 00:08:18.119
And this is the attitude you want to go into documentation with.

00:08:18.119 --> 00:08:24.279
And there are folks across this conference that will preach to you the gospel of documentation.

00:08:24.279 --> 00:08:28.040
But there are a couple things I would like to add in.

00:08:28.040 --> 00:08:30.399
One of them is to modularize.

00:08:30.399 --> 00:08:35.619
Which we did hear about a bit this morning in the keynote.

00:08:35.619 --> 00:08:47.080
So like this beautiful tart, every slice can be divided up equally and stand on its own.

00:08:47.080 --> 00:08:49.359
You want to treat your code like this.

00:08:49.359 --> 00:08:53.080
Generally, how do you know if you need to modularize your code?

00:08:53.080 --> 00:08:57.500
If you have a single script with more than 500 lines, too long.

00:08:57.500 --> 00:08:58.500
You should consider modularization.

00:08:58.500 --> 00:09:04.659
If you're doing more than two scrolls, it's not going to be sustainable.

00:09:04.659 --> 00:09:11.719
So on the left, there is some code that does some spatial processing and will take a while

00:09:11.719 --> 00:09:12.719
to run.

00:09:12.719 --> 00:09:18.520
It also depends on loading in a bunch of datasets and having libraries in your environment.

00:09:18.520 --> 00:09:20.239
And that's fine.

00:09:20.239 --> 00:09:21.239
It will run.

00:09:21.239 --> 00:09:24.159
And the script is going to take a long time.

00:09:24.159 --> 00:09:32.280
But if you modularize, you can go into a few different you can create scripts that are

00:09:32.280 --> 00:09:35.320
named according to what they do.

00:09:35.320 --> 00:09:43.080
So load packages does nothing but load packages for a solid 15 lines.

00:09:43.080 --> 00:09:46.400
Load data only loads the data.

00:09:46.400 --> 00:09:49.880
It doesn't do any extra modeling or spatial processing.

00:09:49.880 --> 00:09:52.159
It just loads the data.

00:09:52.159 --> 00:09:54.320
And they don't have to be completely independent.

00:09:54.320 --> 00:10:00.599
If they need to run sequentially, you can name them 1, 2, 3, and that gives you a signal

00:10:00.599 --> 00:10:03.960
that they need to be run sequentially.

00:10:03.960 --> 00:10:09.760
I'd also like to advocate for a bespoke readme or a very fancy readme.

00:10:09.760 --> 00:10:17.280
A readme is an explanatory document that accompanies computer files or software, according to Wikipedia.

00:10:17.280 --> 00:10:22.280
And I think it gets overlooked in data science from my observation.

00:10:22.280 --> 00:10:27.559
There are three parts of a readme that make it truly bespoke and fancy.

00:10:27.559 --> 00:10:34.039
Context, structure, and key information.

00:10:34.039 --> 00:10:39.799
So your context should answer the questions, what even is this thing?

00:10:39.799 --> 00:10:41.679
Why does this thing exist?

00:10:41.679 --> 00:10:45.039
And what is its history?

00:10:45.039 --> 00:10:49.479
Answer these questions in the beginning of your readme, and it will ground this project

00:10:49.479 --> 00:10:58.679
in what the truth and the true meaning of why you're even working on this.

00:10:58.679 --> 00:11:00.559
The second is structure.

00:11:00.559 --> 00:11:02.559
How is everything organized?

00:11:02.559 --> 00:11:03.880
Where does the data live?

00:11:03.880 --> 00:11:10.640
Where do you actually do the thing to run the analysis and get the output?

00:11:10.640 --> 00:11:14.719
And this will also force you to take a step back from your code and think about it in

00:11:14.719 --> 00:11:18.159
a more structural manner.

00:11:18.159 --> 00:11:20.520
And finally, key information.

00:11:20.520 --> 00:11:24.159
This is where you break out the hate list, and you're going to do the exact opposite

00:11:24.159 --> 00:11:25.719
of the hate list.

00:11:25.719 --> 00:11:29.719
You're going to turn it into a love list.

00:11:29.719 --> 00:11:35.919
And your key information should answer the question of, at the most fundamental level,

00:11:35.919 --> 00:11:39.640
what is the operative component and how is it done?

00:11:39.640 --> 00:11:48.239
So with the truck corridor study, it was a weighted mean, which wasn't apparent from

00:11:48.239 --> 00:11:49.719
the beginning.

00:11:49.719 --> 00:11:55.599
And so instead of leaving it a mystery, I added it in a snippet of code that doesn't

00:11:55.599 --> 00:12:03.000
by itself run, but it gives what is the most important information.

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:06.840
And that's my next and final part.

00:12:06.840 --> 00:12:11.340
Is to leave a gift, not a mystery.

00:12:11.340 --> 00:12:17.159
I have one more video for you.

00:12:17.159 --> 00:12:30.000
This is of a person loading a person using a gift wrapping a gift with very precise clean

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:36.880
lines and they add a little bit of nature at the end, and it is presented on a linen

00:12:36.880 --> 00:12:44.280
tablecloth with candles and pine cones, and I would be utterly delighted to find a gift

00:12:44.280 --> 00:12:45.700
like that.

00:12:45.700 --> 00:12:54.640
And this is what the energy you want to bring in to your project debrief.

00:12:54.640 --> 00:12:57.200
The first thing to do is to take a break.

00:12:57.200 --> 00:13:04.239
Once the project is done, really truly actually done, shut it, put it away, and don't look

00:13:04.239 --> 00:13:07.440
at it for at least two, three weeks.

00:13:07.440 --> 00:13:15.119
And then you're going to come back in and condense and clarify.

00:13:15.119 --> 00:13:22.039
So as I was working through the truck corridor study, I made something like nine R markdowns,

00:13:22.039 --> 00:13:26.080
and most of them did not go anywhere.

00:13:26.080 --> 00:13:32.219
Either they were a dead end or some exploratory analysis or they were worked into some other

00:13:32.219 --> 00:13:34.479
part of the analysis.

00:13:34.479 --> 00:13:38.640
But you wouldn't know that just from looking at these files.

00:13:38.640 --> 00:13:45.039
And if you were going to work on this project, you would have to read through all of these.

00:13:45.039 --> 00:13:50.799
So instead, I broke it down into three R markdowns.

00:13:50.799 --> 00:13:56.679
A readme, a bespoke readme, a summary, and methods.

00:13:56.679 --> 00:14:03.080
And it's much more clear and concise, and we have a couple aspects that are inside those

00:14:03.080 --> 00:14:06.979
markdowns.

00:14:06.979 --> 00:14:13.080
In the markdowns, I've documented not only what, but why.

00:14:13.080 --> 00:14:14.799
So what?

00:14:14.799 --> 00:14:18.159
We used 2019 traffic data.

00:14:18.159 --> 00:14:21.659
That could be a full sentence.

00:14:21.659 --> 00:14:25.640
If I'm looking at this in the future, and I see that this project was taking place in

00:14:25.640 --> 00:14:32.520
2021, and they'd already released the 2020 data, why in the world would they use 2019?

00:14:32.520 --> 00:14:43.000
And it's likely obvious to most of us that 2020 was quite anomalous, which is why we

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:45.960
used the 2020 data.

00:14:45.960 --> 00:14:47.640
It was quite anomalous.

00:14:47.640 --> 00:14:51.599
Also known as a garbage fire.

00:14:51.599 --> 00:14:59.799
Additionally, we set all of the corridors were given scores, and those scores were broken

00:14:59.799 --> 00:15:01.520
into tiers.

00:15:01.520 --> 00:15:05.799
And we set the tier breaks at 15.4 and 26.2 points.

00:15:05.799 --> 00:15:08.640
Those are very specific.

00:15:08.640 --> 00:15:13.239
And it was important, it's not 15.5, it's 15.4.

00:15:13.239 --> 00:15:21.000
And not 26.2 or 30, it's exactly 26.2.

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:25.119
So why would we do that?

00:15:25.119 --> 00:15:29.919
Because our transportation planners used their best judgment given a wide array of factors

00:15:29.919 --> 00:15:35.799
outside of just these numbers.

00:15:35.799 --> 00:15:40.239
I also really advocate for reproducibility.

00:15:40.239 --> 00:15:42.239
You want to record package versions.

00:15:42.239 --> 00:15:47.320
And there are lots of ways that you can do this, including tools like Groundhog, Pack,

00:15:47.320 --> 00:15:50.280
or RN.

00:15:50.280 --> 00:15:51.280
Take your pick.

00:15:51.280 --> 00:15:52.880
Just be consistent.

00:15:52.880 --> 00:15:56.479
I'm also a big fan of a good time stamped output.

00:15:56.479 --> 00:16:01.080
You can integrate a time stamp into the name of the file that you're outputting, or you

00:16:01.080 --> 00:16:05.859
can implement it in, like, a column in a data frame.

00:16:05.859 --> 00:16:11.940
Whatever you do, you need to have a year, month, and day.

00:16:11.940 --> 00:16:15.659
All three.

00:16:15.659 --> 00:16:19.380
So this project is done for me for now.

00:16:19.380 --> 00:16:25.020
And I would love to tell you about how I came to love trucks and see their importance in

00:16:25.020 --> 00:16:31.299
the Twin Cities region and how they're perfect for our future economic opportunities, but

00:16:31.299 --> 00:16:35.700
I still don't care about trucks.

00:16:35.700 --> 00:16:38.419
They're just not my thing.

00:16:38.419 --> 00:16:45.859
But every single person in my office knows about the documentation I made for this project.

00:16:45.859 --> 00:16:52.340
And I am so proud of the work I did about something I don't care about.

00:16:52.340 --> 00:16:56.580
And so at the end of it, I'm feeling less like, oh, I don't care about this.

00:16:56.580 --> 00:16:59.640
I feel a lot like this little crab.

00:16:59.640 --> 00:17:03.979
But instead of a fish, I'm holding up a truck.

00:17:03.979 --> 00:17:04.979
Thank you.

00:17:04.979 --> 00:17:04.979


